        teacherPrep: "Read Guerber pp. 109–119 (Project Gutenberg). Know the eight Stories for the Heart cold, especially Washington's precedents and the peaceful transfer of 1800. Have Meet George Washington pp. 55–63 and an image of the Federal Hall inauguration ready.",
        objective: "Students learn about the first decades of American self-government under the Constitution — the major events of the Washington and Adams presidencies. They understand how Washington's character shaped the presidency itself, why the first peaceful transfer of power was momentous, and what Washington warned the nation about in his Farewell Address.",
        storiesForHeart: [
          "Washington's journey to his inauguration — April 1789. Elected unanimously, he wrote that he felt like a condemned man going to his execution; he would rather have stayed at Mount Vernon. The eight-day journey from Virginia to New York drew crowds at every town. At Trenton, schoolgirls scattered flowers and sang, and Washington wept. He was inaugurated on the balcony of Federal Hall on April 30, speaking in a low, trembling voice.",
          "Washington sets the precedents — every action he took would be repeated or refused by every president after him. He insisted on the plain title 'Mr. President.' He gathered Hamilton, Jefferson, Knox, and Randolph into the first cabinet and kept those quarrelsome, brilliant men working together. After eight years he stepped down voluntarily, setting the two-term pattern that held for 150 years.",
          "Hamilton vs. Jefferson: two visions of America. Hamilton, Secretary of the Treasury, wanted an industrial and financial power — a national bank, protective tariffs, a strong central government. Jefferson, Secretary of State, wanted a republic of independent farmers, small government, and power kept close to the people. Their disagreement produced the first two parties: Federalists and Democratic-Republicans. Washington hated parties and warned against them, but could not stop them.",
          "The Whiskey Rebellion — 1794. When farmers in western Pennsylvania took up arms against the new federal whiskey tax, Washington personally led 13,000 men into the field to suppress it. The point was made: the Constitution is the law, and no one chooses which laws to obey. The rebellion dispersed, and Washington pardoned the ringleaders.",
          "Washington and the French Revolution — as France descended into terror and war, Americans divided bitterly. Washington insisted on strict neutrality, judging the young nation too weak to be dragged into European wars. He had the meddling French envoy 'Citizen Genêt' recalled. His principle: no entangling alliances.",
          "The XYZ Affair and John Adams — in 1797 French agents demanded a bribe before they would negotiate with American diplomats. Adams revealed the insult to Congress, calling the agents X, Y, and Z, and the country was outraged. He built up the Navy but avoided full war with France, at great political cost. It helped lose him the election of 1800 — but keeping the peace, he said, was his greatest achievement.",
          "The death of George Washington — December 14, 1799. A severe throat infection, worsened by repeated bleeding, took his life. He faced death with the composure he had shown in battle; his last words were 'Tis well.' The nation mourned for months. Henry Lee's memorial gave the phrase never improved upon: 'First in war, first in peace, and first in the hearts of his countrymen.'",
          "The election of 1800 — 'the revolution of 1800.' Power passed from one party to another peacefully, without violence or a coup — something that had almost never happened in human history. Jefferson walked to his own inauguration in plain clothes and returned to dine at a common boardinghouse table as if nothing remarkable had happened. Something remarkable had happened.",
        ],
